Dinoponera grandis
is found in a wide variety of environments, with predominance in savannas, at least for Brazilian records. Nests have a random spatial distribution and may have a density of up to 180 nests per hectare (
Tillberg et al. 2014
). Each nest has an entrance without a surrounding mound and may reach a depth of 143 cm ( Paiva & Brandão 1995 ). Despite the relatively large nest size, colonies have on average only 14 workers , which indicates that nests are constantly reused and not completely constructed every generation ( Paiva & Brandão 1995 ;
Monnin et al. 2003
).
Pheidole dinophila Wilson, 2003
has been recorded as nesting within nests of
D. grandis
at more than one locality ( Wilson 2003 ).
